## ğŸ”Œ 1. View Port Mappings of a Container

### Command

$ docker container port <container_name_or_id>


### What it does

Shows how **container ports** are mapped to **host ports**.

### Example
$ docker container port webapp
### Sample Output
80/tcp -> 0.0.0.0:8080


ğŸ“Œ **Meaning:**
Traffic sent to `localhost:8080` on the host is forwarded to port `80` inside the container.

ğŸ§  **Common use case:**
You forgot which port your app is exposed on.

---

## ğŸ“œ 2. View Container Logs
### Basic logs
 $ docker container logs <container_name_or_id>

### Follow logs in real time
 $ docker container logs -f <container_name_or_id>


### Example
$ docker container logs -f api-service


ğŸ§  **Real-world use cases**

* App crashes on startup
* Debugging errors (DB connection, env vars missing)
* Watching logs during deployments

---

## âš™ï¸ 3. View Running Processes Inside a Container
### Docker-native way
$ docker container top <container_name_or_id>


### Example
$ docker container top nginx
### Sample Output

PID   USER   TIME   COMMAND
1     root   0:00   nginx: master process


ğŸ“Œ **Important:**
This shows processes **inside the container**, not the host.

---

## ğŸ–¥ï¸ 4. View Processes on the Host (Not Container)
$ ps -ef | grep <keyword>


### Example
$ ps -ef | grep docker


âš ï¸ **Key difference**

* `docker container top` â†’ container-level
* `ps -ef` â†’ host-level

ğŸ§  Useful when:

* Checking Docker daemon
* Verifying background services
* Debugging resource leaks on the host

---

## ğŸ“Š 5. View Container Resource Usage (CPU, Memory, Network)

### All containers


$ docker container stats             # Real-time
### Specific container
$ docker container stats <container_name_or_id>


### Example
$ docker container stats redis


### Metrics shown
* CPU usage
* Memory usage / limits
* Network I/O
* Disk I/O

ğŸ§  **Real-world use case**

* Identify containers consuming high CPU or memory
* Capacity planning
* Performance tuning

---

## ğŸ” 6. Inspect Detailed Container Configuration
$ docker container inspect <container_name_or_id>

### Example
$ docker container inspect mysiteX


### Filter specific details using `grep`
$ docker container inspect mysiteX | grep -i ipaddress


ğŸ“Œ **Useful inspection data**
* IP address
* Mounted volumes
* Environment variables
* Network settings
* Restart policies

ğŸ§  **DevOps tip:**
`docker inspect` is your **single source of truth** when debugging container behavior.

